711038f-a.title: Manhattan: 10th Street - 5th Avenue
711038f-a.text:
10th Street, west from Fifth Avenue, showing 10-44 West 10th Street
on the south side. 26 West 10th Street, in the middle of the
gIOup of brownstone houses with the second story balcony common to
them all, is the residence of the columnist "F. P. A." (Franklin
P. Adams). 44 West 10th Street is The John Alcen, a 9-story apart-
ment house erected between lWl6 and 1920 on the site of old 42-6,
brick houses. Prior to the 1870Pe this street was numbered east
from Sikth Avenue.
May 29, 1933
P. L. Sperr.
No. 14, the second house from the left, in which Mark Twain lived
when he returned from his world tour in 1901, has been sold by Francis
S. Farr and the new owner will remodell same, according to the New
York Times of April 19, 1938. It is said that during this residence,
the author wrote "To the Person sitting in Darkness," The Tle of a
Eing and his Treasure' and "The Watermelons."

711039f-a.title: Manhattan: 10th Street - 5th Avenue
711039f-a.text:
10th Street, north side, west from and including Fifth Avenue, showing
the Church of the Ascension on the N.W. corner. This was erected
in 1850 by the Frotestant Episcopal Church; this congregation
moved here from its first location, in Prince Street (1839-50).
June 11, 1933.
P. L. Sperr.

711040f-a.title: Manhattan: 10th Street (West) - 5th Avenue
711040f-a.text:
Jest 10th Street, southside, west from (No. 18, left) a
point to the west of Fifth Avenue. The photographer is view-
ing towards Sixth Avenue to show a row of balconaded buildings
bearing Nos. 20 to 38 inclusive and situated in the middle of
this block. No. 26, reputed to have been the home of President
Martin Van Buren, has recently been leased by Franklin P. Adams
(F. P. A. of news fame) for alteration into modern one room
apartments.
une 15, 1938.
P. L. Sperr,
